    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-06-23T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-06-23T16:00:00-05:00" n="679"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d679">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">867N.00/473a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-06-23T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 23, 1937—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>256. Upon the forthcoming publication of the report of the Royal Commission of
                    Inquiry the Department foresees the necessity of <pb facs="0898" n="887"
                        xml:id="pg_887"/> considering a number of questions that may arise as a
                    result of that report and the policy of the British Government with respect
                    thereto.</p>
                <p>In the circumstances the Department wishes to be kept advised fully and promptly
                    by telegraph of all important developments including such information as may be
                    discreetly obtainable revealing the views and intentions of competent
                    government, parliamentary, and other circles in Great Britain on this
                    subject.</p>
                <p>It would be helpful in this connection to have your views as to the attitude
                    likely to be taken by Parliament and by important Jewish leaders in Great
                    Britain in the event some radical solution of the Palestine problem, such as
                    partition, is recommended by the Commission and supported by the Government, and
                    as to the possible attitude of the Government in case of strong opposition to
                    the proposed solution.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
